{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T18:29:45.359050+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-07T03:56:08.379922+00:00", "id": 13525455, "conceptrecid": "13525453", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13525455", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13525453", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13525455", "metadata": {"title": "Effects of white-nose syndrome on regional population patterns of 3 hibernating bat species", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13525455", "publication_date": "2016", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Hibernating bats have undergone severe recent declines across the eastern United States, but the cause of these regional-scale declines has not been systematically evaluated. We assessed the influence of white-nose syndrome (an emerging bat disease caused by the fungus Pseudogymnoascus destructans, formerly Geomyces destructans) on large-scale, long-term population patterns in the little brown myotis (Myotis lucifugus), the northern myotis (Myotis septentrionalis), and the tricolored bat (Perimyotis subflavus). We modeled population trajectories for each species, on the basis of an extensive dataset of winter hibernacula counts of more than one million individual bats from a four-state region over a 13-year time period, in combination with data on locations of hibernacula and first detections of white-nose syndrome at each hibernaculum. We used generalized additive mixed models to determine population change relative to expectations, namely how population trajectories differed with a colony's infection status, how trajectories differed with distance from the point-of-introduction of white-nose syndrome, and whether declines were concordant with first local observation of the disease. Our results indicated that population trajectories in all species met at least one of the three expectations, but none met all three. Our results suggest, therefore, that white-nose syndrome has affected regional populations differently than previously understood, and not as the sole cause of declines. Specifically, our results suggest that in some areas and species, threats other than white-nose syndrome are also contributing to population declines, declines linked to white-nose syndrome have spread across large geographic areas with unexpected speed, and the disease or other threats led to declines in bat populations for years prior to disease detection. Effective conservation will require further research to mitigate impacts of white-nose syndrome, renewed attention to other threats to bats, and improved surveillance efforts to ensure early detection of white-nose syndrome. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Ingersoll, Thomas E.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Sewall, Brent J.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Amelon, Sybill K.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Myotis lucifigus", "Myotis lucifugus", "Myotis septentrionalis", "Perimyotis subflavus", "Pseudogymnoascus destructans", "emerging infectious disease of wildlife", "enfermedades infecciosas emergentes de la vida sil", "generalized additive mixed models", "modelos aditivos mixtos generalizados", "monitoreo de poblaciones", "population monitoring", "Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/36580d788cf8bf0dce84645e05373105", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/81e53e739ef6dd8ef6f3696c848d6868ffbb9e854cf07e5f4930537de8f35990", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/UU2AXNNC", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/UU2AXNNC", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/68cdd268def53c3a9c68a08c2552466f!/b119794-122294", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "has